column92: Collision between U.S. Navy vessel to free swimming whale; final state of whale is unknown. Per Jan Larson Director of Environmental Operations and Planning: On 27 Mar at 1:59pm (PST), the USS PRINCETON was in transit to the Pacific Northwest from Southern CA waters when there was a possible whale strike. The location of the possible whale strike was approximately 48 miles west of Point Loma and to the southeast of San Clemente Island. Visibility was excellent, but no marine mammals were sighted prior to the possible strike. The PRINCETON was underway at 22 kts when a shutter was felt and the aft lookout reported blood and flesh visible in the water. After the ship completed a hard turn, a spout was detected approximately 1500 yards from the location of the possible strike. No other information was available to confirm that a whale strike occurred and no further whale sightings or indications of marine mammal presence (e.g , whale spouts) were observed. The PRINCETON was undamaged and resumed transit to the Pacific Northwest.

column92: Attempted 4 times to secure animal for necropsy, however, the difference in tides did not allow for the animal to beach completely in a secure location. The beach the animal was located is highly active making necropsy very dangerous. As the animal washed in and out of the surf, we were able to collect barnacles, and examine the right side of the whale with certainty. The whale was washed in parallel to beach with only the right side visible. The whale was also orientated belly up, allowing for the sex to be determined. There were numerous barnacles, 20+ under throat, and distal lateral edge of right flipper, and along the distal caudal edges of fluke. No skin left on the fluke made photo fluke ID impossible. Large shark bites and scavenging in armpit and fluke. 6inch perfect circles were scavenged on the right under the throat region. There was a distinct 0.5m hole across just below the eye, could be worn from rocks or other trauma (not certain if prior to death or post mortem). Pictures are located on the MLML stranding network computer. Blubber slabs were taken for tagging study (collaboration with Jim Harvey, ONR project). There was an abscess near fluke that we biopsied. No other samples were taken due to the nature of the wave activity.

column92: Very good condition; a couple of post-mortem predator chunks take out on left ventral side, mid-section; slight rubbing from rocks on right dorsal side.

Necropsy Report, Dr. Duane Tom: Morphologic diagnoses of pathological lesions: -Note: Although freshly appearing externally, there was significant autolysis internally. -Large cavernous abscess along L dorsal thorax. Fracture of a left transverse vertebral process with reactive bone and sequestra, though subacute trauma and osteomyelitis another posible rule-out. Gross necropsy summary diagnosis: The animal appears to have succumbed an injury consistent with an impact trauma along its left dorsal body by a large object (ship strike) resulting in severe musculoskeletal trauma and subsequent necrosis of the tissues. The fracture and reactive bone that communicated with the resultant cavernous abscess may indicate chronicity due to a previous injury that would be consistent with the superficially adjacent cutaneous scars, or osteomyelitis associated with the more acute suspect impact trauma.

column92: Animal stranded alive late in the afternoon of 6-11-14. TMMC MBO volunteers were observing the animal and recording respiration rates. MLML staff took over for MBO staff and continued keeping respiration records. The animal was being rolled around in the surf a fair bit, but kept consistent respiration rates for most of the observation period. Scratches on the ventral surface were noticed, likely due to rubbing against the sand as it was being moved around. The animal was able to un-strand itself as the tide increased and swam north of the initial location. It then re-stranded twice more further north. J. Goldbogen (Hopkins Marine Station, Stanford University) assisted with tracking the animal later that evening. Visual contact with the whale was lost just before 8:00 PM PDT that evening. Animal was reported as stranded dead late in the morning of 6-13-14. MLML and MBO staff went out to the initial stranding location and verified that it was the same animal that live stranded earlier in the week. MLML staff went back to the location and monitored the carcass to see if it could be secured. The carcass continued to roll in the breaking waves and was unable to be secured. Staff with the MLML network and from Marine Life Studies (MLS) continued monitoring the carcass each day. The carcass remained in the breaking waves. Members of the public reported that the carcass "exploded" sometime on 6-14-14. On 6-14-14 blood was occasionally exiting the mouth, and some tissues were exiting the body through the mouth. The jaws appeared loose, possibly indicating that the joint had broken between the upper and lower jaw. Most of the skin had sloughed off from both lateral sides of the animal. Both pectoral fins and parts of the fluke and dorsal fin were removed, likely due to the near constant rolling. By 6-15-14 birds were actively scavenging the carcass and larger pieces of tissues were leaving the body. Two vertebrae from the whale were found on the beach, and one was collected by C. Serraino from MLS and transferred to the freezer at MLML. Last confirmed location for the carcass was at 36º 39.31'N, 121º 49.31'W around 8:30 PM PDT on 6-15-14. Carcass was not sighted on 6-16-14.

NO external signs of trauma, entanglement scars or predatory wounds. It initially washed ashore at Dockweiler Beach last night around 1900h and we got word of it around 2230h. The LA Lifeguards/LA County Beach and Harbor (AKA: LA County) unsuccessfully tried to tow it off last night, but were unsuccessful. I arrived on the scene about 1000h this morning and was joined by folks from LA County Museum, American Cetacean Society, and the Roundhouse Aquarium (Manhattan Beach). Due to the holiday weekend and the popularity of this beach, LA County was adamant about getting the whale towed off the beach as soon as possible. They gave us a little over 2hours to work on the carcass. We started with getting photos, measurements, and collecting epi-biota. We then took some skin and blubber samples for genetics to determine stock. We also collected some muscle for Rachael Cartwright (CSU-Channel Islands). In addition to that we took a fecal sample for biotoxin analysis and collected some intestinal worms and a few plates of baleen. LA County then (unsuccessfully) attempted to tow the whale off (at low tide mind you) using a bulldozer and two towing lifeguard boats. The carcass was rolled over a few times so we did get a decent look at the dorsal surface as well. The whale was finally towed off the beach at 1900h. Whale floated back near shore and was towed off multiple times over the next 17 days, finally washing ashore and taken to landfill in Encinitas.

column92: Identified as fin whale (Balaenoptera physalus) by asymmetrical coloration on mandibles (gray right mandible) and throat grooves, bicolored baleen, overall coloration, and genetics from SWFSC. Animal was originally reported by the United States Coast Guard at Yerba Buena Island 1/5/17 when a vessel, NYK Triton, had what appeared to be a whale size animal or possible whale carcass on its bow. As the vessel turned into Oakland Bar channel, the carcass fell off the bow and sank. The whale was then reported on 1/7/17 floating in Oakland harbor off of Howard Terminal. Two personnel from TMMC went out to assess the animal, take pictures and collect basic samples. Due to the storm with large swells, high winds and rainfall the animal was left floating next to the Howard Terminal. The USCG received a report of the animal floating in the Oakland harbor channel on 1/9/17 causing hazards to passing vessels. The animal was then towed to Angel Island by the Army Corps of Engineers where it was tied off to a pier near Blunt Point until weather conditions improved. Due to repeated intense weather and storm debris clean-up, the Army Corp of Engineers was only able to land the carcass on Angel Island on 1/25/2017. Due to continued bad weather and boat availability, a small team was only able to get to the carcass for a partial necropsy on 2/6/2017. A second team returned to Angel Island to conduct a more complete necropsy on 3/2/2017. See necropsy report for more details.

column92: The carcass was originally reported as floating off of Agate Beach in Marin County the evening of 25 May 2017. The carcass was confirmed on land at Agate Beach (37.899783¿N, 122.712575¿W) the morning of 26 May 2017. Due to the timing of the tides and logistics, three researchers from TMMC and CAS examined the carcass on 5/26/2017, taking initial measurements and samples. A full team conducted a necropsy on 27 May 2017. The carcass was identified as a known animal (CRC-1540) by Cascadia Research Collective on 5/26/2017. CRC-1540 was first identified off California in 1999 and seen in at least 11 different years off California mostly in the Santa Barbara Channel area. Genetic confirmation on the match can be made from a biopsy taken in 2006. She was documented with a calf in two years. There may be additional sighting information from the Sea of Cortez, Mexico since she also matches the CICMAR catalog.

Ryan Clapper (Reporting Party) I was in San Francisco last week with my wife and we decided to hike the Golden Gate Bridge. About half way up we realized there were 3 to 4 humpback whales feeding in the bay below us. A boater was cruising by at high speed and never slowed down. He may have seen one of the whales breathing far away and tried to get closer for a photo and went right over a humpback. SFPD works on the bridge and I made them aware of the situation. We couldn¿t get a vessel number from the boat since it was so far away. So I emailed a photo to the SFPD and a local news station that aired it the next day. http://www.gulfster.com/Daily/2017PictureGallery/hump-back-whale-golden-gate/index.html

A team was assembled in case of a potential necropsy. However, once the team got there the whale was still floating and even with a lower tide, the carcass was inaccessible due to mud. The team tied off the whale that evening. On 4/4 Parker Diving service and a team from TMMC towed the whale to Angel Island. At this point in time the animal was still in relatively fresh condition. Due to the timing of tides, weather, and daylight hours the necropsy needed to be postponed until Tuesday April 9th. On 4/9 the animal was high and dry on Angel Island but was now in a moderate state of decomposition. A full necropsy was conducted.

There was one partial and one full-thickness laceration along the caudal peduncle and a partial thickness laceration along the dorsal aspect of the fluke. See necropsy report for more details.

column7: Phillips 66 Refinery, next to the docks
column92: This animal was initially reported on 5/6/19 floating next to the docks at Phillips 66 Refinery. The animal was tied off to the docks there until boat services were available. On 5/9/19 the animal was then towed to Angel Island. Due to boat availability and tides the team could get out to do the necropsy until 5/14/19. Parts collected for CAS - two pelvic bones, right auditory bullae, small section of baleen, tissue sample.

column92: Carcass was towed without permission from NOAA/JV on 05/13 and dropped approximately 8 miles outside the Golden Gate. It washed ashore early 05/14/2019. As of 05/20, unable to tow it back into SF Bay for necropsy.

column7: just inside Anaheim Bay on south jetty wall
column18: large area of trauma on left side of head, hemorrhaging visible on the right side of head, consistent with a vessel collision
column92: Animal had a large wound on the left side of the head, hemorrhaging seen on right side of head; consistent with vessel collision. Level A filled out off of photos provided. Carcass was towed offshore by lifeguards on 6-1-19. Carcass restranded on Huntington Beach in front of Hilton, south of pier on 6-3-19. Beach staff buried the carcass before reporting to NMFS, so no examination

column7: Port of Long Beach, Pier J near cruise ship terminal
column18: Came in on the bow of a Carnival Cruise ship
column92: whale came in on the bow of a Carnival Cruise ship that came into Port of Long Beach. Vessel had left Mexico the previous night. Large area of trauma surrounding a crease on the whales back just in front of dorsal fin. Crease was also surrounded by blue paint. Crease and blue paint are likely from animal being pinned to the bow of the ship. There is hemorrhaging observed on the opposite side of the body from where the crease was, it is believed that the vessel collision was ante-mortem. Right pec flipper broken at insertion and jaws were separated, both of these are believed to be post-mortem.

column31: When it came ashore on 7/6/19, it loked like some of the bones may have been broken
column92: Keith Poe was with whale on 7/2/19 and 7/3/19 when it was about 1 mile off Pt. Dume. Whale came ashore at Will Rogers State Beach on 7/6/19 and was buried on the beach

Moderatedly decomposed upon first observation. Was not there on June 30, so decomp occurred elsewhere (at sea?). SMALL TISSUE SAMPLE collected, available to NMFS or CICRU (or others) for species ID, however baleen was clearly present.

The carcass was first reported on Blue Beach at Chadbourne Gulch on 4 July 2019. A team from the Noyo Center for Marine Science made an initial visit to the carcass on 4 July 2019 for photos and measurements but the carcass was rolling in the surf. On 5 July 2019, a team returned to the carcass to take more detailed measurements, photos, and samples.

column7: Point Reyes National Seashore, rolling in the surf at Sculptured Beach
column92: The carcass was first observed rolling in the surf at Sculputured Beach on 5 July 2019. It was then observed and photographed on the beach near Elephant Rock on 6 July 2019. A team from CAS and TMMC attempted to respond to the carcass on 7 July 2019 but were unable to reach the beach due to the tide. The area where the carcass was located at Elephant Rock was only accessible at a -1.5 tide and all upcoming low tides are too high. Identification of the carcass and all Level A data are from photos.

column7: Point Reyes National Seashore, Wildcat Beach
column92: This carcass was originally reported to TMMC in the surf at Wildcat Beach in Point Reyes National Seashore on 7/21/2019. PRNS staff confirmed the carcass was still in the same location on 7/22/2019. CAS, TMMC, and PRNS conducted a complete necropsy on 7/23/2019. Although the entire carcass was intact, the skull was fractured with the posterior portion of the cranium loose on the beach. On necropsy the rostrum was fractured and had some bone bruising. COD was blunt force trauma consistent with ship strike.

First encountered on Aug.14, 2019 at 12:54pm. 34, 16' 28.626000"N, 119, 46' 17.556000"W Mother was with the carcass that was floating dorsal side up. Second encounter was on Aug 15, 2019 at 2:17pm. 34, 11' 47.796000"N, 119, 46' 36.402000"W Carcass only, ventral side up. No mother whale in sight. No sharks. Western gulls on top. Condor Express whale watching boat found Mother exhibiting grieving behavior.

column7: In San Francisco Bay, 1/2 mile NW of Alcatraz Island
column92: Ship strike witnessed by a member of the public and reported to the USCG, and responded to by the whale watching vessel Kitty Kat. Struck by container ship MSC Azov (captain denies), in SF bay. Whale floated on the surface, bleeding, until it finally appeared to have died. It was last seen floating near Kirby Cove, just west of the Golden Gate Bridge. It did not appear any place on the outer coast after this last sighting. **On October 7th, a report was made to CAS of a "whale sock" (blubber but no bones) at Mussel Rock Park in Daly City. This particular area is known for its high deposition of dead marine mammals. CAS responded to collect tissues for DNA analysis and the blubber was not located. It is unknown if this is the remnant of this humpback, as there were not identifiable features.

column7: Floating ~1 mile north of Point Sur
column92: Carcass first reported floating on 10/11/19 by a local fisherman. Stranded on beach at Point Sur State Historic Park on 10/13/19. TMMC responded on 10/13/19 but could not access the carcass due to locked gates. MLML (Lauren Cooley + Daphne Shen) responded on 10/14/19, but could not conduct a full Level A examination due to unsafe location of carcass in surf. Photographed, collected skin sample, and estimated length only.
